Their meet- ings, necessarily secret for the most part, on account of the lady's position, took place at the house of a friend (c. 68. 68). But not even the possibility of discovery restrained the ardor of the poet’s soul. He poured lorth his feelings most simply and unrestrainedly in a series of charming trifles.
